<Document>
<name>Route des Grandes Alpes</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Route des Grandes Alpes</h2><p><i>France · Thonon-les-Bains (Lake Geneva) to Menton (Mediterranean)</i></p><p><b>720 km, 17 high passes, 11 above 2,000 m. The classic French Alpine traverse.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>393 km (244 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Realistically 5–7 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>July–September (Iseran often closed Oct–mid June; Galibier closes in winter)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closure dates for Iseran and Galibier; cyclists in Tour de France pilgrimage; hairpin overconfidence; weather</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>877</td></tr></table><hr><p>720 km, 17 numbered passes, 11 of them above 2,000 m. Conceived in 1909 by the Touring Club de France as an Alpine traverse following older mule paths, largely complete by 1937. Driving it end-to-end is one of the great driving achievements in Europe — a slow, deliberate week. From Lake Geneva's vineyards through Col de l'Iseran (2,770 m, the highest paved pass in the Alps) and Col du Galibier (2,645 m, made famous by the Tour de France) to the citrus terraces of Menton on the Mediterranean. Plan around the Tour in July (passes close on race days). The Iseran is the linchpin — if it's snowed-in, the route is broken.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Col de l'Iseran</b> — 2,770 m, highest paved pass in the Alps. Stone chapel on the summit. The road usually opens last week of June; on bad-snow years not until mid-July.</li><li><b>Bonneval-sur-Arc</b> — Listed among 'most beautiful villages of France' — slate-roofed stone houses, no concrete, no overhead wires. Glacier source of the Arc river just upstream.</li><li><b>Col du Galibier</b> — 2,645 m. Most-climbed pass in Tour de France history. Henri Desgrange monument; the riders pass it with their hats off in homage.</li><li><b>Briançon</b> — Highest fortified town in the Alps (1,326 m); Vauban's 1690s star fortress is intact and UNESCO-listed.</li><li><b>Col d'Izoard / Casse Déserte</b> — 2,360 m. Just below the summit on the south side, the 'Casse Déserte' — a moonscape of orange-yellow scree pinnacles. Tour de France climbing legend.</li><li><b>Col de Turini</b> — 1,607 m. Used in the Monte Carlo Rally for decades — every rally driver in Europe has crashed somewhere on its hairpins. Now in summer just a beautiful beech-forest pass.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
